What is counted? The ČSSD in Prague knows neither Voldemort nor pastry
The new ČSSD councillors in the capital will apparently have to overcome obvious language barriers if the members of the Prague Board and the City Council are to understand their renewed ODS colleagues.
The Aktuálně.cz period "examined" the members of the new ČSSD Council to check their knowledge of the marked Slang language that has emerged in recent years in the Council, when the current members of the coalition governed Prague.
The codified dictionary that used Prague's political cream during the previous period, by Mayor Pavel Bém, includes some of the metropolis' best-known characters, situations and causes.
Surprisingly, it has been found that the new councillors hardly understand these well-known concepts.
At least, that's what they say.
"Who is Voldemort?"
"The truth is, I don't know."
"I'm more of a novice in Prague politics," Culture Councillor Lukáš Kaucký said during the "colleague" terminology exam.
And as far as the veteran politician is concerned, Karel Březina reacted the same.
You may know the concept of "golf hole".
"It's possibly the only expression of all the ones you asked me what I use from time to time."
"If not, I don't normally use slang."
From the glossary, whose definitions were published by the newspaper Aktuálně.cz last June before the SDG voting congress, the editorial staff chose six examples, in particular those that are especially related to the municipal authorities of Prague.
The Socialists had to explain the concepts "Voldemort", "Prague golf's biggest hole", "go to the pastry shop", "bull's neck", "treason of the capital" and "shield".
Three councillors agreed to take the test and a fourth, Antonín Weinert, who will eventually be responsible for education in Prague, initially agreed, but did not pick up the phone again.
The fifth councillor, Petr Dolínek, directly refused to do so.
"I don't get into these things or do I intend to value how much fun civic democrats have."
"What does matter to me is how we will understand each other in the execution of our programs," he said.
As we have seen, councillor Lukáš Kaucký allegedly would not have noticed that the above title is an expression about an influential businessman and a friend of former Mayor Bém, Roman Janoušek.
To Kaucký the word "Voldemort" says nothing; the only term he got right in the exam is "the biggest golf hole in Prague".
"It's about the Blanka tunnel," says Kaucký, who immediately adds: "But I rather know it from the news."
"I'm going to have to sign up for a language course," he jokes.
Karel Březina is not the only one who recognizes the Blanka tunnel in the golf hole, but also the Councillor for the Environment Lukáš Plachý.
Afterwards, both Social Democrats know who Voldemort really is and Lukáš Plachý even knows where to find that character; In addition, he suspects the meaning of "going to the pastry shop".
"I think it means going to a company in Prague"; Plachý is soon revealed that it is the headquarters of Janoušek's companies.
Like Březina, he indicates that such knowledge was obtained from the news, but that he does not use such vocabulary.
According to the participants in the test, among the Social Democrats there is no such familiar glossary of colloquial terms.
"I asked my teammates, but it really seems like we don't have anything like it."
"Rather, among ourselves we use nicknames, sometimes abbreviations or play on the names," says Prague ČSSD chairman Petr Hulínský, whose party colleagues call Hulda.
"At school they called me Bříza, but I don't know if my classmates also call me that," confesses his own nickname Karel Březina.
The newspaper Aktuálně.cz tested the name and it works.
To his party colleagues, Weinert is Děda (similar to "yayo") or, less friendly, Dědek ("old"), Representative Miroslav Poche, with whom they associated before the elections cheating during party sponsorship, is nicknamed "Igráček" ("playmobil") by some of his peers.
Nicknames are also the only expressions that Social Democrats tolerate in speech within the party.
Hulínský does not like to be called Hulda, but the newspaper Aktuálně.cz even discovered other nicknames for this Prague president.
"The doctor of truncheon rights" apparently recalls that Petr Hulínský obtained his doctorate in law at the police academy in Bratislava.
The government wants to limit the torture of "witches", as published in a brochure
Women considered as witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They are usually elderly, unable to work, for example, for health reasons, single and have no children.
Women who "become" witches are sent to an isolated area, so that they do not harm the rest of the village.
"Men rarely suffer such a fate."
"Nor are healthy young women isolated, because they help with the work and have children," explains a nun who, in the capital of the West African state, Burkina Faso cares for more than a hundred women expelled from their communities in a special residence.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual "social measure".
He issued an information leaflet that should help prevent the witch hunt.
However, this has a drawback.
"More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso cannot read," warns the newspaper Die Standard about the disadvantages of written awareness.
Accusations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Burkina Faso's neighbour Ghana, 72-year-old Ammy Hemmah died last week when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with petrol and burned her.
The news appeared on the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to an unfortunate accumulation of circumstances.
According to his version, the woman caught on to the oil used for ritual anointings.
It went up in flames when the group wanted to "drive out evil spirits" from the woman.
The isolation of the "witches" is supported by people of all educational levels.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso: "The devourers of human souls always represented a danger," he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government is trying to quell the witch hunt, in Gambia last year the president still participated.
"Gambian President Jammeh, following the death of his aunt, launched a wide-ranging hunt for witches who had allegedly been linked to his death and had attempted to kill the president himself through black magic."
"To help him, he brought shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president's personal escort, forcibly took men and women randomly chosen from Gambian villages to the president's property in Kanilai," Amnesty International said in its report.
On the farm, the arrested people had to drink a potion of herbs with hallucinogenic effects that, in addition, caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of those arrested did not survive the stay on the farm.
After international pressure, they finally released around a thousand detainees.
Bakala's tenant: heated with charcoal stoves and signs a higher rent
The elderly and tough man walked through the doors of the RPG Byty customer service center of "coal tycoon" Zdeňek Bakala, the largest private owner of flats for rent in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he carried some documents with the new rental contracts of three floors: his, his daughter and his son, who is serving his sentence.
All three have just been caught by the liberalization of rents.
Instead of CZK 3,500 a month, the son will pay from next year 4,100 kroner for a two-room apartment with separate second-class kitchen.
"In addition, it does not have hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler," the man shows with his finger in the new contract of his son, over whose signature he has full powers.
"But I signed it," he explains, half-angry, half-resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which described the new rental conditions as "incorrect and indecent", recommends tenants not to sign the new contracts and to wait until December 7, when it will publish a guide informing on how to proceed in these cases.
But, before this, man only makes a gesture.
"Everyone says one thing," he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a great testing ground for liberalisation.
After the New Year it will happen with the vast majority of flats that, in the Czech Republic, were so far under a regulated rent.
Therefore, Aktuálně.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
RPG's mining waiting room is one of four in Ostrava and, by Tuesday at nine, it was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and next to them a machine to pick up a number.
"Rent 2011", can be read on a light button on its touch screen.
When pressed, a piece of paper with a number comes out of the machine.
There is almost no time to read "157" and the number already appears on the large screen located at the top of the room.
In a second, you are in the queue.
Soon after, an elderly couple arrives to ask, but the crowd in the living room is not here because of the new rents.
Most people come to solve common problems, such as in the past: settlement requests, insurance issues, and similar matters.
The letters with the new rental contracts will arrive in Ostrava to the mailboxes of the tenants of most of the 44,000 flats belonging to RPG around mid-November.
RPG Byty proposes in the letters an increase in rent of between 15 and 38%.
On November 18, a special window opens in the customer service center for new rentals.
"It's been running for a week, so it's just starting," reply, after briefly hesitating, the workers who are in it when the client introduces himself as a journalist.
Liberalization and the old flats for miners of Bakala are the most sensitive issues in the area.
Before the elections, they were already discussed loud and clear by the deputy speaker of Parliament, originally from Ostrava, Lubomír Zaorálek, of the ČSSD, and now they appear continuously in the newspapers of the area.
"Twenty years later I want a new floor."
"They didn't even change my damn bathroom plate," vents the man mentioned in the introduction.
According to the workers, at the moment retirees come mostly to check if they receive a discount on rent if they sign on time, as promised by the special offer of RPG.
Half of the discount on February's rent will also be received by the remaining tenants who sign the new contract before December 15.
However, the window of mining "liberalization" certainly fails to dispel the avalanche of doubts.
"Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, only about forty or fifty people asked about the rent in 2011," estimates the window employee.
Meanwhile, RPG proposes on the web and on its boards to hold individual meetings on contracts when necessary.
If the two parties do not reach an agreement on rent, the matter must be resolved by an independent judge.
"This is not a threat, but information about the only possible and completely lawful course of action," RPG warns in its pages.
"No one is going to be judged here," says one of the employees of RPG Byty and a man who is on the street in front of the customer service center gives him, at least in part, the reason.
"I receive a pension of 13,000 and I have 5,000 left for food; I don't have the means to go to court," he says.
But, immediately, the employee sows doubt.
"We'll see."
"Mr. Zaorálek warns them in the media not to sign, so maybe people will wait," he says.
Rent regulation will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic at the beginning of 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, increasing it is an economic necessity.
"Current rents still do not cover even the amounts needed to maintain the community fund," recalls Pavel Klimeš, director of the residential portfolio of the company RPG Byty, who adds that the neglected state of the community fund that angers tenants is, for landlords, the main reason for increasing rent.
While during the five years between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest four billion in apartments with rents, in the four years that will go from 2011 to 2014 the figure will increase to 5,200 million.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling, in front of the waiting room seats, now repeats some data that stands out in red.
"The rent increase in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, i.e. more than 90% of RPG properties."
"In addition, it will always be at most CZK 7.50 per square meter per month," the screen states.
Only increased by 38% the rental of 400 apartments in the RPG portfolio.
"In such cases, this is an increase from extremely low amounts, of SEK 19.66 per square metre," says RPG.
In 2,600 apartments, the rent will remain unchanged next year.
RPG Byty promises that liberalization will not hit rents all at once, but will escalate between four to eight years.
In addition, it adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money from the rent increase (see the graph) again in the flats, mainly in savings in heating: new windows and heating.
Priority will be given to people who sign the rent increase agreement.
Architects have understood that offices also need childcare
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the Arch.Design company.
Nobody would say that it also hides inside a small nursery with everything typical of such facilities: colorful walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch.Design employees have been able to come to it.
The architectural design company Arch.Design, from whose studio many well-known buildings in Brno came out, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-nursery.
The company employs around 90 people, mainly at the age of the baby boom and wanted to allow architects and draftsmen to return to work soon after motherhood.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, childcare is one of the benefits it offers Arch.Design to its workers within the framework of its social program.
Construction and architects thus have the possibility of combining a demanding profession with childcare.
The mini-nursery was the brainchild of Arch.Designu's own employees and, with the support of management, managed to secure funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's mini-crèche is financed through the European Social Fund within the framework of the Operational Programme for Human Resources and Employment as well as the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding granted (an endowment of more than CZK 2.8 million) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, hire qualified staff and services.
When the funding runs out (two years), the Arch.Design company is obliged to keep the mini-nursery running with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and the company Economy Rating contributed to the presentation of the financing application.
The care of children is in the hands of qualified personnel; In addition, a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present all day for their care. The nursery currently accommodates children with no age limit, although most of them are under three years old.
Since it is a "mini-nursery", it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with the shifts they come more during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible to suit the needs of parents and the children of all workers have the same right to use the nursery, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is an individual teaching and care, the contents of the mini-nursery programme are comparable to the programme of regular pre-school education.
In it children not only play, but also receive quality teaching: from basic learning to school readiness, they teach even English.
The class not only has toys and board games, but also a computer for the children.
The presence of young children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up children late from school when they are away from their workplace.
Thus, parents are more productive while working.
Not surprisingly, this naturally generates a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is among the firm companies that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program reinforced the marketing of personnel.
The house of bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. See Gaudí's interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs resemble the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its skeleton-like shape, locals nicknamed it "the house of bones."
Its organic forms, its striking colors, the novel use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a façade reminiscent of scales and the omnipresent gently curved lines, all this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaudí.
The cover of the house plays with dreamlike lines, delicate colors and textures taken from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, a certain geometry, rhythm and carefully thought out order is observed.
At night, the entire façade of the house looks even more impressive, since it is illuminated in such a way as to improve the brightness of the colors.
It meanders and the twisting of the shapes continues to surprise us also inside.
Corrugated wood copies window frames, railings, door ornaments, peepholes and signs.
Casa Batlló, which is located in the Eixample district at number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Grácia, arose from the remodeling of a house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on demolishing the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of carrying out a novel and cheaper reconstruction.
However, Casa Batlló, made up of several apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
The architect Josep María Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in his project plans emerged ornaments for the representative apartment of the property owner and the mosaics used on the façade.
On the façade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration on Casa Batlló's proposals was the beginning of Jujol's successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of Gaudí's Casa Milá and Park Güell, where other pieces of it are located.
Due to its organic shape, locals soon after its completion nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows began to call it "the house of yawns".
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, appears the sword of St. George, patron saint of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of the building hide religious motifs.
Gaudí designed in the house a unique system for the time of central heating with ventilation vents and typical chimneys.
Its tilt of forty-five degrees may seem strange.
During the construction, Gaudí did not respect at all the building regulations of the moment and did not allow himself to be influenced by them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permit from the beginning, although evidently in it the indicated data on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the city council was so shocked with the result that it asked for it to be corrected.
He was annoyed, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, quite the contrary: just fifteen days after the request of the city council, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
On the lower floors the owner himself settled.
In the gallery on the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The six-storey house is completely crossed by a staircase leading to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connecting space.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the rooms and a larger group can communicate in this way without problems, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with Gaudí's reconstruction, not only got a new façade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles that cover the inner courtyard and skylights.
The game with the two colors provides maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which instead absorb the sun's rays.
Anyone can visit Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage list.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and most ornate apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that it is a very beneficial business and expanded the visits to the common area and the attic, including the roof terrace.
The price of the entrance to the monument is not insignificant, reaching 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and holders of tourist cards get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of the entrance of other Gaudí constructions in the city.
