How to choose the mattress and box spring: women and men look for different things
No pompous frame for the bed; What really gives its quality to a good bed is the surface to lie down, that is, the mattress and the box spring.
First of all, they must complement each other perfectly so that they adapt to the specific users.
During the election, numerous elements come into play, including the weight, height, state of health and sex of the owner.
Also important is the type of interior in which the mattress and box spring are located.
A typical example?
For example, in a weekend cabin that does not usually have heating, latex mattresses should not be used because they "heat up" more slowly.
In addition, they tend to weigh considerably more than the usual polyurethane mattresses.
It is therefore necessary to turn them around more frequently.
If the channels in the center are not properly aerated and are on a firm base, they keep moisture inside. Mold may even appear underneath.
When choosing a bed, customs also influence.
Anyone who has spent a lot of time abroad often uses a very high mattress with a soft layer and will have trouble feeling good on a lower, harder surface.
"Almost every hockey player who came back from the NHL complained that they didn't sleep as well here."
"For their crushed shoulders, heels and hips they needed mattresses with a soft layer of viscoelastic."
"These types of mattresses are also recommended for people with diabetes who have nervous system problems, so they receive poor information from the joints and skin," explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in padded furniture.
Many hockey players, like other customers, have long preferred memory foam mattresses.
"Today there is no problem, because they have these suitable Tempur and the Italian Magniflex, but also the Czech brand Tropico."
You no longer have to be an NHL player to appreciate viscoelastic.
This "miracle" works in a very simple way.
It optimizes its rigidity and shape depending on the heat absorbed or adapts to its body heat.
Nothing puts pressure on; During the night, he will not spin like after a tough match.
Simply, you sleep better.
Viscoelastic also works as protection against sores.
When choosing the size of the mattress, add to its height the length of your feet, that is, between 21 and 34 cm.
A man or woman with a height of around 180 cm will need a bed between 210 and 220 cm.
The minimum width for one person should be, in a double room, 90 cm, in total 180 cm.
In the case of single rooms, for example singles, it is recommended at least between 120 and 140 cm.
So that a possible visit is also comfortable.
"If not, you can apply a simple rule to calculate the width: when lying on your back, you should have your hands comfortably shrunk towards your elbows," advises engineer Helena Prokopová, an expert at Cechu čalouníků a dekoratérů, who has been dealing with the problems of healthy sleep and furniture ergonomics, a subject she teaches in specialized schools, for many years.
In the double rooms, everyone needs their own box spring and mattress, so during the purchase you have to pay attention to combine the height of the mattresses.
Otherwise, it will be necessary to mount the box springs at different heights, which is not always possible in all beds.
Foam mattresses should have a minimum height of 14 cm, models with spring interiors a minimum of 15 cm, of which at least three centimeters are for the layer that adapts to the shapes and softens.
"When touching it with your hand or when you settle on the mattress, you certainly shouldn't notice the springs," warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a certain type of box spring.
Fully padded bedrooms, in which the mattress and base are like Siamese, do not make sense in the bedroom.
Mattresses breathe poorly and you can not wash their cover, which is often done today.
And, given that every night we perspire between 0.2 and 0.75 l of sweat, it is clear that after about five or seven years the mattress will begin to remind us of a large (and congested) sieve.
For this reason, specialists reject slogans that speak of a mattress life of up to 25 years or even a lifetime warranty.
However, everything has a but.
That's why sellers give a tip: on mattresses with a width of 120 or 140 cm, take care carefully about cleaning and washing the cover, but better add a mattress protector that can be easily removed and washed.
Although mattress covers with zipper closure are currently manufactured around its perimeter, so when opened they remain in two parts (something very important for washing and the size of the washing machine!), their manipulation in larger models (and by a single person) when lifting the mattress may seem like a fight between a flyweight and a heavyweight.
In bed, instead of a box spring, do you have a firm board?
Never!
At most for the beds designed to spend one night visits.
However, it should make (if you do not already have them) ventilation holes in the board and should be used with a mattress with springs inside and a minimum height of 15 cm with the springs in bags (like the German Taschenfederkern) and a soft layer.
Polyurethane mattresses should not be used on such bases.
For non-articulable sheet bed frames containing between 14 and 18 sheets, latex mattresses or sandwich mattresses (for example, a combination of latex and coconut fiber) can be used, although it is always better to have a box spring with a greater number of sheets, 28 or more, in which the sheets of the lumbar area are reinforced and their stiffness can be regulated.
Articulating sheet bed frames should not be used with a spring mattress, as it does not react to recline.
In addition to adjusting the stiffness of the blades, shoulder protection can also be used.
It is a special fixation of the sheets that allows you to press or even tilt the sheets in such a way that they "circle" the shoulders perfectly during sleep.
For men who have very broad shoulders, this is very important.
Even mattress manufacturers remember them who, in the "masculine", began to use a softer area precisely around the shoulders.
They also remember women, for whom they put a softer area around the hips.
For the most demanding customers, there are bed bases with cross structure or slats with the so-called multitorsion damping.
The pressure is distributed between different points and the tension is lowered.
You should also keep in mind that, even if you use the right mattress and box spring, if you use a bad pillow (large and "fluffy"), most of the advantages will disappear.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow should support the head and the corners can only reach the shoulders, so that the muscles of the shoulders can be relaxed.
The recommended suitable size is 50 x 60 cm, something normal for example in Scandinavia.
When lying on your side, the pillow should be at the same level (when combined with the shoulder reinforcement box spring or the softer area of the mattress) as the height of the shoulders.
Modern mattresses have something to do, it seems, with the original straw-filled mattresses.
Manufacturers continue to use, more and more often, natural materials or, at least, mixtures.
In fact, organic mattresses are fashionable.
The petroleum-based raw materials, from which polyurethane foam is made, are filled with natural oils, for example castor or soybean.
In fact, virtually all known manufacturers use soybeans.
"Biological, in the case of mattresses, means that the centre is made only of materials of natural origin," explains Petr Vašíček of Tropico Plus.
Likewise, natural substances are used during the manufacture of the mattress cover, one of the first aloe vera.
But you can also opt for microcapsules, which release a fresh aroma of forest or lavender.
There are also differences for men and women.
While men "cool off" with breeze plant extracts, so that the mattress cover absorbs heat and refreshes the body, women prefer to "heat" the cover.
Red pepper extract improves blood circulation, so that women feel warmer.
The favorites currently?
Mattresses made of cold foam, which are more porous, with an adapted cell structure, which makes them more permeable than normal polyurethane and offer more permeability.
The combination of various rigidities of cold and viscoelastic foam allow to manufacture mattresses of different areas that know perfectly where the head, shoulders and heels go.
A good quality mattress will cost you from seven thousand crowns up.
Those that perform a therapeutic function usually have a lower VAT, since they are considered as health means.
The first to gain this advantage in the Czech Republic was Gumotex.
It is difficult to save on mattresses and box springs.
Sometimes offers from manufacturers or sellers can be approved, sometimes offering two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers Duofreeze mattresses with a memory foam attached to the cover for 11,990 crowns.
The second is available free of charge.
The era of viscoelastic with an open cell structure and high density began with the "cosmic" material of Tempur.
Initially it emerged as material for NASA, because during takeoffs astronauts were subjected to enormous overload.
Tempur softens with heat and hardens with cold.
Consequently, the human body, warm, exerts a perfect effect and optimally adapts its pressure.
Therefore, it is ideal to prevent sores from occurring, but also to improve comfort during sleep.
Memory foam is not only used in mattresses, but also for sanitary products, for example for pillows that are placed under the legs and relieve them, as well as their circulation.
National manufacturers, for example, use Eucatherm C or Twinsaver foam and the like.
More and more parents are using people-tracking devices to monitor their children
Fear for children leads more and more people to think about controlling them by GPS.
The system, initially designed for vehicle tracking, can also track the movement of people and thus contribute, for example, in cases such as the disappearance of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
At the moment the device is about the size of a matchbox, but will soon be reduced to the size of a watch.
Many people were afraid of the case of the missing Anička and began to learn about the means available to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of invading your privacy.
"We all try to tell each other that this is not about spying, but about another means to reduce the chances of a tragedy," says Petr Pilin of the company Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices on the Czech market.
"I recognize that, in certain cases, such devices can be abused, for example if they are put in someone's bag without their knowledge, but we have not yet encountered such cases."
"Most customers actually buy it for security reasons," Pilin adds.
In his opinion, children should always know what the "box" is for and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočková warns about the fact that if the child does not want to wear it, he will simply throw it away.
"Even the youngest children are very creative about intentionally losing certain things if they want to avoid being controlled."
"Before, parents relied heavily on mobiles, but they could be turned off as easily as the tracking device," says Bočková.
In its view, it is questionable whether, in the event of an attack, such a device is actually useful.
"If it is a prepared abduction, the perpetrator will almost always check whether the child is carrying any kind of electronic device that can reveal his location."
"Now it's the phone."
"As the use of tracking devices spreads, it will also look for them, since their sale will undoubtedly be made with a lot of advertising."
"In such cases, criminals are always one step ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
However, he adds that such devices can help in the event of an improvised attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert Čech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both vehicles and people, even if the tracking device is immediately destroyed after an attack, its presence can help.
"You can configure the device to regularly send the position after a certain period."
"If it is harmed, it will at least facilitate the last position of the person in question."
"More expensive devices have a built-in tilt meter, so if the person simply slips and stays still, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question," says Čech.
Such a service can even be obtained with smartphones with navigation, on which only special software needs to be installed.
The problem with current tracking units is that at the moment they are devices with a size similar to a matchbox or smaller mobile phones.
Therefore, they can be lost.
According to Macro Weil's Pilin, that's why tests are currently underway with devices that look like a digital clock.
"In addition, they will have the added advantage that a potential attacker may not identify the device."
"Or to identify him after a certain amount of time, which can buy the police time," he adds.
Even if the tracking devices are worn on the wrist or hanging, they will still use the same technology used for vehicle tracking.
This is the checking of the position with a GPS system (which is used in the usual navigation in the car) combined with the function of a mobile phone that communicates the current position.
The army has enough wicks to surround the entire Czech Republic. But they only last two years
The Czech army bought 445 kilometers of fuse to light explosives.
Already last year the Ministry of Defense added 224 kilometers of wick to its arsenal.
Therefore, they have stocks for 225 years.
The problem is that the useful life of the wick is two years, four at most.
The army bought the fusha for explosives from STV Group, a.s. for forty million kroner.
The General's staff responded to MF DNES by justifying the purchase of such a huge amount of wick by saying that soldiers need 60 kilometers of wick a year for training maneuvers.
According to the calculations of the army pyrotechnics, with whom MF DNES was contacted, it is nevertheless decided that, in such a case, all generals, high-ranking officers, and even secretaries and cleaners should carry out such maneuvers with frequent use of explosives every year.
Neither Defense Minister Alexander Vondr nor army captain Vlastimil Picek wanted exempt.
Only in this way could it be justified for the army to spend sixty kilometers of fuse.
Such a length is equivalent to 25,000 explosions.
Even if it were, the army would have enough stocks for more than ten years.
If, on the contrary, as the experts say, for the initial training of each new professional arrives with a maximum of two meters of wick, the army would have with the new purchase (even adding the consumption of the units of engineers or special) sufficient stocks for the 225 indicated above.
The soldiers of the rapid intervention brigade recently personally complained to Minister Vondra that they say that they have hardly any ammunition for various weapons, so even target practice is limited for money.
And let's not talk about the lack of underwear.
"I also cannot understand that they repeatedly buy such quantities of wick from us."
"But it's their decision and they'll certainly know why they act like this."
"For us, the army is a good customer who, as a company, we try to satisfy," admits STV Group Chief Commercial Officer Jan Děcký.
Defense Ministry spokesman Jan Pejšek defends the hundreds of kilometers of wick also saying that it will have stocks of this "ammunition" for at least ten years.
However, Jan Děcký of STV Group points out that the fuse only has a service life of four years and, in the case of pyrotechnic products for the army or police, two years.
"If stored in perfect conditions, it can last up to four," says one of the soldiers who, due to possible criticism from the army, does not want to give his name.
After the end of its service life, each munition must be carefully checked to see if it remains reliable and will not harm soldiers.
But these trials are not free and require additional investment.
Another argument of the Ministry is that, by buying 445 kilometers of wick, it got a discount.
"They cost us 60% less than last year's order of 244 kilometers," says spokesman Pejšek of the Ministry of Defense's shopping center.
Just for comparison: the annual consumption of fuse by police pyrotechnics, who eliminate the ammunition of the Second World War or that left by the Soviet army, has not exceeded 1,500 meters for years.
In addition, the police always ask only for just enough ammunition to exhaust the ammunition before its useful life is over.
They decided on this for safety reasons for pyrotechnics and, in addition, more modern and reliable types of wick can be obtained in the meantime.
The Ministry already has clear difficulties finishing tens of thousands of tons of ammunition from the Warsaw Pact era, when the Czechoslovak army of two hundred thousand people was preparing for a campaign on the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnics with whom MF DNES spoke, after a couple of years the following problem will occur with the current one: hundreds of kilometers of old wick will have to be eliminated, which is now being bought "cheap".
Until now I continue to live from the contacts I got thanks to the contest
Winning the "Entrepreneur of the Year" contest helped Lukáš Pytloun sell his hotel franchises.
Last year, the "Entrepreneur of the Year" contest was won by 28-year-old entrepreneur Lukáš Pytloun from Liberec.
His success story looks like something out of a movie.
Lukáš Pytloun loved to travel.
Abroad, he realized that Liberec needed quality accommodation at a good price.
With the savings he gathered with seasonal jobs abroad and a loan from the bank, he bought a half-demolished house composed of five floors.
Considering that he was still in his junior year at university, he was really brave.
"Today, the value for money of accommodation in our area has prompted me to do something about it," says Lukáš Pytloun.
He began renting the first reconstructed floor to foreign workers.
All the income he earned was invested back into the building, which he gradually converted into a 54-room pension.
Since then, in seven years in business, he managed to gradually open in Liberec four pensions, two stylish restaurants and two hotels with a total capacity of around 300 in all categories of accommodation.
The most comfortable of all was, until recently, the four-star design hotel Pytloun.
However, this year opened another of the same quality.
"We have just signed a contract with a hotel in Ostrov u Tisé, to which we have sold our franchise concept, and other people are showing interest in a Pytloun franchise," said last year's number one entrepreneur.
"This sale of licenses for the opening of hotels was greatly helped by winning the 'Entrepreneur of the Year' contest," adds Pytloun gratefully.
The victory increased his fame and popularity both in Liberec and in the surrounding area.
"People recognized me on the street, they still complimented me often and, I must say, I was very nice," he recalls.
Without a doubt, he recommends everyone who wants to try a company that participates in the contest.
But he believes that it is not necessary to win, but that participation is already beneficial.
He states that, so far, he continues to live off contacts and acquaintances that, without the competition, he might not have obtained.
"With some people I met thanks to the contest I have started to collaborate regularly."
The fame associated with success, in his opinion, also included in the employees,
in total about seventy.
"I've seen them show greater loyalty and are proud to participate in something that got mainstream recognition."
"It's by no means my own personal success, it's the result of the hard work of the whole team."
"It's only my name that appears on the front page," Lukáš Pytloun says modestly today.
I wish my successor a quieter year than we have had at Farmet.
The euphoria over victory soon dissipated from the impact of the crisis.
Thanks to the victor's hard work, Farmet may have already passed the worst.
Farmet company owner Karel Žďárský received first prize in the latest edition of Vodafone's "Company of the Year" contest last year at Prague's "Slavic House".
The jury appreciated his efforts, which led to the conversion of a small technical workshop in Česká Skalice into a firm with a turnover of hundreds of millions.
"I can say that the award not only encouraged me, but all my collaborators and improved our confidence to fight against the competition," says last year's winner.
