A survey that reveals ridiculous rules
The Absurdity of the Year poll is part of the business tournament for the fourth time.
It has already managed to eliminate some ridiculous rules.
The unknown winner of the new edition of the Absurdity of the Year survey was the obligation to bring documents to the administration that officials can access online.
The decision was made by more than a third of the nearly four thousand voters.
For example, the social security administration asked for an extract from the commercial register, although its officials can obtain it with two mouse movements.
Thanks to the survey, this has changed.
"The Czech social security administration will no longer ask for an extract from the commercial register when it carries out a check on the insured's taxes," said ČSSZ spokeswoman Jana Buraňová.
The aim of the Absurdity of the Year survey is to consult the rules and regulations to be respected by companies and entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic and to try to eliminate those that are absurd.
This year it is part of the business tournament of the publication Hospodářské noviny for the fourth time and begins to create a fan base among the general public as well.
While last year's edition had the participation of three thousand voters, this year it practically reached four thousand.
And this is not surprising, since we still have several legal obligations that must be respected simply in order to trade.
"Perhaps in terms of the number of papers required for tax filing," says Karel Havlíček of the Association of Small and Medium-sized Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic.
For years, simplifying business rules has been a stated goal of all governments.
However, compared to the rest of the world, the situation improves especially in the Czech Republic.
According to the World Bank, from the point of view of the conditions for owning a company, the Czech Republic is in 74th position, that is, eight positions worse than last year.
The Absurdity of the Year contest was first held in 2006 and is repeated in the same way every year.
Anyone can indicate some administrative or bureaucratic absurdity every year between April and the end of September, when the contest closes.
Proposals can be made on the www.firmaroku.cz website. The contest organizer then chooses seven candidates for the "anti-prize" and, during October, allows the public to vote online through www.firmaroku.cz/absurdita and www.ihned.cz.
The absurdity that receives the most votes wins.
For this year's survey, more than a hundred were submitted, including 105 rules and regulations that make no sense.
The examples were sent by businessmen, professional associations and journalists.
Among the "finalists" of the competition were, for example, the requirement that vehicles for the maintenance of roads and highways pay the toll or that employers with twenty employees, two offices and two bathrooms paint the walls every two years.
The list of this year's seventy proposals is published on the pages of the competition.
The announcement of the competition, which always takes place at the beginning of November in Wenceslas Square in Prague, is part of an event in which personalities from the political and social world usually participate.
This year, for example, Eva Svobodová, director of the Association of Small and Medium-sized Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic, and Petr Kužel, President of the Chamber of Commerce of the Republic, attended the competition.
"Economic prosperity cannot be maintained if the state continually hinders entrepreneurs, so my goal is to eliminate each year a minimum of thirty paragraphs that currently unnecessarily complicate trade," Industry and Trade Minister Martin Kocourek announced.
Efforts to eliminate absurd regulations are not in the water.
In 2007, what bothered people the most was the obligation of the employer to communicate three days in advance to the business office of the permanent operating area, the intention to go with a stand to a fair or exhibition.
This obligation was eliminated in the new industrial law.
The obligation that came second in number of votes in 2007, i.e. the communication to the labor office by its foreign workers of work trips of up to 30 days, was eliminated in the so-called green card law.
And to the third goes the loser.
The Absurdity of the year 2009 was the regulation for physiotherapists to have in their practice a large mirror, a refrigerator and two floor scales.
That is why this year the Ministry of Health issued a communication saying that it had eliminated the obligation to have a refrigerator.
