Police made arrests during a public auction at the Agricultural Fund building in Plzeň
Anti-corruption police have made several arrests at the Agricultural Fund building in recent days.
Detectives handcuffed a local media entrepreneur and real estate entrepreneur Luboš G.
It appears that he attempted to manipulate an ongoing public auction for the restitution of rights in such a way that the land auctioned would be received by a precise interested party.
He was to pay Luboš G. half a million kronor for it.
"At the moment I can only say that the police are looking for a person for bribery during a public auction and public tender," Pilsen chief prosecutor general Antonie Zelená told Právo, adding that she could not immediately release further details about the ongoing investigation.
After twenty-four hours, the police released the 46-year-old businessman.
On the way in which he could influence the public auction, given the little official information, one can only speculate.
Agricultural Fund spokeswoman Lubomíra Černá responded to Právo's questions by saying that the police actually carried out the arrest at the Pilsen headquarters and it was during a public auction.
"This is a customer, not one of our workers," he said.
According to Černá, the public auction is called "Call for proposals for land transfer in accordance with the land law" and is held when several interested parties appear in relation to the land offered.
"These people, during the call, offer a value higher than that of their restitution, which must be transferred before the value of the land is announced."
"Based on the offers, the order of the buyers is determined and then the Agricultural Fund transfers the land to the person offering the highest offer," the Fund spokeswoman explained.
Luboš G. had information on who was going to apply for the invitation and, since he is also an interested person because he acquired various restitution rights, he proposed to those interested in the land that he would not participate in the auction.
For this favor, he was charging a commission.
This would explain why, at the time of arrest, he had so much money on him.
Luboš G. had special contacts in the Pilsen Fund for some time.
It was included in the case of former PF chief Václav Sankot, who was charged with dispatching the replacement of land for which a construction decision had already been issued.
For example, Luboš G. has just obtained from the Fund land planned for the construction of public infrastructure, particularly on the site where a major road to the Borská pole industrial site is to be built.
Later, he exchanged them in a very beneficial way with the magistrate for a house in the historic center of the city with a much higher value.
In this case, the municipality had to intervene because, otherwise, the blocked land would prevent construction.
Families will have to pay additional expenses of several hundred crowns per month
From January, households will have to pay not only for all types of energy, but also for water and electricity, heating supplements and, in some cases, higher rents.
Consequently, families will have to take out of their wallets, from January, several hundred kroner a month more than now.
The price of electricity increases by 4.6%, gas by around 2%, in some cities they will have to pay up to 10% more for water supply and many also increase the price of central heating.
The increase in electricity for families living in apartments should amount to about 100 kroner more per year than now.
However, major electricity suppliers reduced prices, as support for energy production from renewable sources, particularly photovoltaics, has increased.
However, gas becomes moderately more expensive, especially at a time when heating is used more and, therefore, consumption is higher.
In this case, they must also have a couple of hundred more crowns a year.
While electricity and gas become more expensive across the country, the price change of central heating varies from place to place.
The price increase is mainly planned by the largest municipality.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Králové will pay about SEK 50 more per month for central heating from January, while families in Liberec will pay more than SEK 1,000 per year.
Residents in Prague will also have to bear a 9% increase in the price of water and heating, especially in case the city increases the rent of infrastructure.
If the rent does not change, Pragueans will pay an additional 6.8%.
Prices in Prague, however, will remain among the lowest in the entire country.
In northern Bohemia, where current prices are among the highest, both rates will rise by 7.4%.
They can significantly increase the rental prices of 450,000 rented apartments in Prague, where the regulation will end in January.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns around 2,500 flats in Ústí nad Labem, will increase rent from January by up to 100%.
The company will take to court those who do not agree with the new rent.
Regulated rents, which benefit residents of around 300,000 flats, could increase by up to 10% next year.
Young Czechs get drunk on Fernet and rum. The beer is no longer in mode, because it takes effect slowly
Fernet, rum, vodka and even good whiskeys stolen from their parents.
These are the drinks that cause young drinkers under fifteen years of age to end up in medical care.
Children who end up lying in the hospital continuously to overcome the hangover are no longer an exception.
This stems from the experience of doctors who encounter such cases in hospital pediatric admissions.
"Drinking beer or wine is no longer fashionable, because they take a long time to get them drunk."
"Now the fashion is strong alcoholic beverages," Luděk Pelikán, head of paediatrics at Hořovice Hospital in central Bohemia, told Právo.
"When they manage to grab their father from the cupboard, it can be whiskey, but it's usually Fernet and vodka."
"Vodka has the advantage that it is lightened with juice and that it doesn't smell as much," he explains.
This is also confirmed by the spokeswoman for the Motol University Hospital, Eva Jurinová.
"Normally, it's usually Fernet or rum."
"Those are modern alcoholic beverages, particularly among schoolchildren."
"In some cases, they use brandy that they picked at home," adds Jurinová.
According to Chief Pelikán, thirteen and fourteen-year-old drinkers usually appear in hospitals.
Before Hořovice, where he has worked since this year, he worked for a decade in paediatrics in Motol, where ambulances took young people from nearby areas.
"A girl had to enter maybe four times."
"It started at the age of twelve, when they brought her with 3.5 of alcohol in her blood, in addition to a mixture with ecstasy," says the department doctor about this case.
"I was at the Holešovice fair at some dance party."
"The interesting thing is that her mother was not surprised that her daughter disappeared 48 hours," the boss is surprised.
It is precisely the lack of interest of parents or even their clear tolerance towards drinking by their children that is considered the main cause of the increase in alcohol consumption among young people.
Experts point out that, in the case of children, one cannot properly speak of dependence.
"Alcoholic is understood as a person who has a chronic dependence on alcohol for several years, with all the phenomena associated with it, which does not occur in children."
"In those who drink alcohol repeatedly, it is rather due to a systematically failed social or family environment," explains Chief Pelikán.
According to spokeswoman Jurinová, forty drunk children were hospitalized this year at the Motol pediatric clinic until mid-November.
However, the statistics only show those who come with severe poisoning and must remain in hospital.
Young drinkers who, after the mobile medical examination, go home with their parents or the police, do not count.
In addition to the cases in which children simply gather after school and drink brandy, for Pelikán there are three seasonal ups and downs that should be mentioned: Halloween, New Year's Eve and the end of the school year.
"In such a circumstance, they drink for bad grades or, on the contrary, celebrate the start of the holidays."
"On Halloween I have seen up to seven drunk children in admissions at a time," adds Pelikán.
Drinkers who spend the night detoxing under the supervision of doctors, paradoxically, have the advantage that the next day they do not suffer a terrible hangover at home.
Morning headache, caused by dehydration and lack of glucose, is avoided with the injection of a serum with glucose and with the nutrients that the body lacks.
"They take it much better, because after the hectic night, they get up well and it doesn't hurt at all."
"They're just confused about where they are," says Pelikán, adding that patients often lose their good mood at least when they see the expenses they've generated.
The transfer by ambulance and hospitalization in a room for serious patients comes to cost a dozen thousand crowns.
"I have often used the cost as a means of educating them, when on the visit I tell the children directly how much their drunkenness has cost and that they would have to spend the whole summer in a youth job for you to earn enough to pay for that night," adds Pelikán.
Health insurance, in his view, perhaps as a regressive measure, which often reimburses people for treatment costs, does not do so for children who drink.
Two L-159 aircraft are for the first time in the hands of others in Spain
Two L-159 aircraft out of a total of five, for which the Czech Ministry of Defense replaced the Casa C-295M aircraft, left on Tuesday for Seville, where the aircraft manufacturer Casa - EADS is located.
It is the first time such a device has been in the hands of anyone other than the Czech army.
At the moment, they were only abroad for practice or demonstration flights.
This is the two-seat version L-159T1, which until now was used by the Czech army and was still in a state of flight.
The remaining three aircraft are the single-seat L-159.
These are still kept in Aer Vodochody and the intermediary of the sale, the company Omnipol, already took them over last week.
Jan Peješk of the defence press department says it is not yet known when the planes will be physically removed from Vodochody.
"The L-159 single-seat aircraft, on the other hand, were separated from the long-repaired aircraft, without additional investment or contribution from the Ministry."
"The two-seat L-159T1s were exchanged in their current state," Pejšek told Právo.
He added that the army is not running out of two-seat aircraft, since in May 2009 the army signed a contract with Aer Vodochody for an amount of SEK 200 million for the construction of four unnecessary L-159 devices for two-seaters.
One of the new aircraft was already received by the army in July, the other will be delivered by the end of the year.
According to Pejšek, EADS committed to adding the aircraft to the equipment of some allied countries.
"The contract clearly states that EADS is the one that retires the L-159 aircraft and that they will be used for pilot practices in NATO countries."
"It is therefore up to the buyer to decide how to use them in this framework," says Pejšek.
The newspaper Hospodářské noviny published ahead of time that, for example, the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
The exchange of five L-159s for a Casa aircraft and the purchase of three other aircraft for 3.5 billion kroner were approved last year by the government of Mirek Topolánek.
The Ministry of Defence did not call for tenders for the purchase and negotiated directly with EADS.
The current defense directorate claims that the exchange promotes the future export of L-159s abroad.
The Czech army acquired 72 aircraft from Aer and only uses 24, so it wants to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa aircraft is likely to have legal consequences.
The European Commission has already denounced the Czech Ministry of Defence before the European Court of Justice because it should choose the aircraft by holding a European tender and not contacting a single manufacturer.
The army has already received three Casa planes and the last one should arrive at Prague Kbely Airport in fourteen days.
An index finger longer than ring finger indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men who have a longer than ring rate are subject to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
That's the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday in a British cancer journal.
It could depend on the level of testosterone, the male hormone.
"Our results indicate that relative finger length may be a simple test of prostate cancer risk, particularly for men aged up to 60 years," said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
Therefore, the finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, particularly if this characteristic is associated with genetic risk or other harmful factors, such as family health problems, according to Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009, it followed with a British counterpart more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients and, simultaneously, 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the indica finger of the right hand shorter than the ring finger.
They were just as likely to get prostate cancer as 19% of those whose fingers were the same length.
In the case of men with an index longer than the ring finger, this risk was reduced by 33%; For men under 60% the reduction reached 87%.
The relationship between the length of the two fingers in question, determined in the prenatal period, reflects different levels of hormones to which the fetus is exposed in the womb.
A lower testosterone level corresponds to a longer index.
Previous studies indicated that testosterone influences the development of prostate cancer.
The great Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told ČTK that he is aware of the study, but that he does not think the relationship between finger length and cancer can be "fully demonstrated".
