Support for democracy in Latin America continues to grow, as well as support for private companies.
Crime is a greater concern than unemployment.
Moreover, in much of the region, Brazil is seen as a more influential country than the United States.
These are some of the conclusions of the latest Latinobarómetro survey conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been held regularly since 1995, it makes it possible to monitor changes in attitudes in the region.
In the results of this year's survey, conducted in September and early October, two related issues stand out.
The first is the relatively lively humor prevailing in Latin America.
The second is the growing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased considerably in several countries on the Pacific coast of South America (see Table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy has increased from a low 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after suffering a big drop in output last year.
However, only half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the region, are convinced democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Figure 2).
Some 44 per cent of respondents in the region said they were satisfied with the way democracy works in practice in their country, the same figure as last year, but considerably higher than the 25 per cent recorded in 2001 (figure 3).
Some 34 per cent said they trusted their country's Congress and 45 per cent trusted its Government, the same number as last year in both cases, but considerably higher than in 2003 (17 per cent and 24 per cent, respectively).
A decade ago, economic turbulence in Latin America severely affected support for democracy.
The fact that it has persisted during the global financial crisis is likely due to the fact that many Latin American countries were only hit by a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, a stronger social safety net has helped protect the poorest.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty only increased marginally in 2009 and has fallen again this year, to 32 percent.)
However, mood varies considerably from country to country (see Figure 4).
Brazil's strong economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a general feeling of progress.
Such sentiment is less common in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more severe and violent crime has increased.
For the second time since surveys began, more respondents in Latin America are citing crime, rather than unemployment, as the most serious problem facing their country (see Figure 5).
Some 31 per cent say they or a close relative have been a victim of crime in the past year, down from 38 per cent last year and the lowest percentage recorded since 1995.
The more positive economic returns are reflected in greater support for private enterprises and the market economy: about 71 per cent of respondents in the region say that private enterprises are indispensable for development, up from only 56 per cent in 2007 (see figure 6).
Some 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, up from 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela feel the same way (and 80% support private companies), although its leftist president, Hugo Chávez, is expropriating numerous private companies.
Brazil is the country with the greatest leadership in the region, as indicated by 19% of respondents (compared to 18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, the same figure as last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% a year ago).
However, the United States is considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela holds such titles in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
