But problems may still arise if the electoral authority declares that Mr Célestin, who has little support, if any, has made it to the second round.
With the cholera epidemic raging in the country and more than a million earthquake survivors still living in tents, large abstentions are expected.
When the time came, many Haitians wanted to vote, but were unable to do so due to a lack of organization.
Some 250,000 identity documents, needed to vote, had not yet been distributed shortly before the elections.
The stakes are high.
Aid donors see the election of a popular and legitimate government as an essential step in Haiti's reconstruction.
And, as has become clear, so do the Haitians themselves.
Tiptoeing toward the center
In the weeks since losing her husband, Cristina Fernandez, Argentina's president, has enjoyed widespread sympathy among the public that has boosted her popularity rating by 20 points to more than 50 percent, the highest level since her election in 2007.
Still, whether it can turn it into a successful campaign for a second term in next year's elections will depend on whether the clearly affected Mrs. Fernández sets aside the intransigence of her late husband, her predecessor and political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
And, at this point, the indications are inconclusive.
Mr. Kirchner, who continued to take charge of economic policy even after his wife succeeded him as president, had a habit of drawing up budgets that underestimated tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the presidential couple to spend the additional revenue at their discretion.
In theory, Ms. Fernández's government lost its majority in Congress last year.
However, the opposition is divided, a situation that has worsened after Kirchner's death from a heart attack on October 27.
Some dissenting members of the ruling Peronist movement have clashed with Ms. Fernández.
However, after chaotic sessions in which one deputy punched another in the face and other deputies accused the government of bribery, Congress decided to reject the 2011 budget.
"I'm not going to argue," the president said.
The 2010 budget will therefore apply to next year, which will give the President even more leeway in spending it.
The economy is improving considerably: it is likely to grow by as much as 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is currently at 11.1 per cent, but numerous private estimates, in addition to the wage demands of the unions, put it at around 30 per cent.
Mr Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina was on the brink of economic collapse, made growth and poverty reduction his priorities, rather than controlling inflation.
He refused to negotiate with the IMF, pressured the private sector and had INDEC, the statistical institute, adapt official inflation statistics.
Will President Fernández now moderate these policies?
He has convened meetings between the private sector and union leaders.
In addition, its officials say they want to limit salary increases next year to 18%.
The economy has been boosted by the high prices of Argentine agricultural exports in the world.
However, inflation has limited the boost to growth achieved by a major devaluation in 2002.
Perhaps for this reason Mrs Fernández is showing signs of wanting to restore Argentina's financial links with the rest of the world.
Earlier this year, the government reached an agreement with bondholders who had refused a previous forced restructuring of debt that Argentina had not paid in 2001.
At present, it seems that Mrs. Fernández is about to enter into an agreement with the creditor governments grouped in the Paris Club, to which she owes about 6,700 million dollars.
The Kirchners always insisted that this would not involve IMF supervision, as is customary.
However, last month Amado Boudou, the Minister of Economy, announced that the Fund will offer "technical assistance" to develop a new national consumer price index, which seems the prelude to the cleaning up of INDEC.
It is unclear whether President Fernández wants to remain in politics when her term ends, considering that she no longer has her husband by her side.
If he does, he will need to win the support of the middle class, much of which has grown tired of Kirchnerism.
When Argentines return from their summer vacation in March, the wave of sympathy for her will have subsided.
If she wants to win another election, she will have to decide whether or not to calmly repudiate many of her husband's policies.
Half a hurrah for China
Taiwan's voters are slowly moving closer to a kind of closer union with the mainland.
What does Taiwan think about its big brother across the strait?
More than 7.5 million voters, 70% of those eligible, turned out on Nov. 27 to elect mayors and councilors of five urban districts in what appears to be a broad assessment of President Ma Ying-jeou.
Mr Ma himself has become an advocate of sentiment for the continent, forging innovative business links, including a partial free trade pact, the biggest change in relations with China since 1949.
Mr. Ma passed the test, but narrowly.
Although his Kuomintang (KMT) party ended up winning three of the five mayoral elections, it failed to win a majority of the vote.
Instead, the Democratic Progressive Party (DPP), which has favored full independence from Taiwan, won virtually 50% of all votes to KMT's 45%.
If it had been the presidential election, Mr. Ma would be in trouble.
Since his election two years ago, his party's share of the vote has declined by about 8%.
For the first time, the PDP tied with the KMT in the town halls.
The elections showed typical elements of Taiwanese elections, including noisy campaign trucks and large crowds with flags and lightly clad girls dancing.
There was also the mysterious assassination attempt of rigor.
Sean Lien, the son of Lien Chan, honorary chairman of the KMT, was campaigning for one of the KMT candidates the night before the election.
A man in the crowd shot the young man directly in the face, wounding him and killing a passerby.
The funny thing is that it has not been possible to determine if the man intended to harm Lien or take revenge on the candidate.
In any case, says Tsai Ing-wen, the leader of the PDP, the shooting affected the elections, sowing suspicion about the PDP and causing voters to lean towards the KMT.
Perhaps the only big winner of the campaign was China.
It was surprising that the issue of the continent itself was not discussed.
Instead, the candidates talked about public accommodation and job creation schemes.
Taiwan normally enjoys its de facto independence and detests China's military threat.
As a result, the KMT often avoids publicizing its ties to the government in Beijing.
But this time too, the PDP avoided encouraging anti-China sentiment.
It responds to the new awareness that Chinese trade is essential to Taiwan's economic survival.
For his part, Mr Ma stated that his policy towards China had been confirmed to be acceptable to the majority of Taiwanese.
The Beijing government is expected to continue to bribe them with trade, in line with its strategy to bring Taiwan back into the fold.
China wasted no time sending a negotiator to Taipei to prepare a summit on investment protection and medical cooperation.
He would certainly also like to achieve political integration, but first things first.
It is best to wait until the 2012 presidential elections for this.
In any case, the PDP has reinvented itself.
Two years ago it was in a bad situation: its former leader, Chen Shui-bian, was jailed on corruption charges.
President between 2000 and 2008, he openly instigated explicit independence.
However, under Ms. Tsai's leadership, a new generation of moderates has emerged and the PDP is striving to attract professionals and young people.
Ms. Tsai has been welcomed as the DPP's candidate for president, as has Su Tseng-chang, who served under Chen.
Now his party is doing its best to show that it can also have relations with Beijing.
Ms. Tsai announced plans to create a group of experts to act as a point of contact between the PDP and China, provided that negotiations can take place without preconditions.
Ms Tsai tells the Taiwanese public that her party represents a "reliable alternative" to Mr Ma's hasty approach to China.
Mr. Chen seems furious about the change.
In a statement issued from his cell, he said the PDP candidates would have fared better if they had insisted that Taiwan is an independent country.
He even ordered Mr. Su, a pragmatist, not to run for president.
Even without Mr. Chen interceding, the PDP will have difficulty choosing among its possible candidates.
The KMT must also make an examination of conscience.
Mr Ma's valuations have been poor, despite impressive economic growth; KMT candidates have not wanted to campaign with him.
Its lack of popularity seems to be mainly due to unemployment and the growing gap between rich and poor.
A KMT spokesman says he will restructure his cabinet as well as local teams.
Large DPP displays suggest that Taiwan's support for rapprochement is limited.
At the same time, most Taiwanese consider economic integration with China to be inevitable.
According to Antonio Chiang, a well-known columnist, "the point of no return has already been crossed."
Grammy Nominations: Jazz singer Esperanza Spalding is the surprise choice in the Breakthrough Artist category.
