He is back (Hasbro/Playskool, $40, for 3 years and older), with a backpack full of question letters designed to turn a car ride into a session with a witty self-correcting workbook.
If you are wary of giving your child his smartphone, here you will find three independent alternatives.
VTech's MobiGo ($60, ages 3 to 8) is the cheapest and easiest to use, featuring a qwerty keyboard; While the games don't teach as effectively as the Leapster Explorer ($70, ages 3 to 12), it's the first major tune-up in the Leapster lineup, with a newer, brighter display.
No version is compatible with old cartridges.
Fisher-Price's iXL ($90, ages 3 to 7) uses an iTunes-like system to present games and e-books, and has an SD card slot that lets you view family photos.
