It's fun to do a maze of blocks to see if you can find the way out.
It is also durable.
Ours was able to leave the kitchen table and even hang out inside our dog's mouth.
A more moderate side of law enforcement is promoted in China
Like an urban drill sergeant, Tang Shenbin set the pace in a city square, sternly inspecting the nervous people in his charge, quietly issuing orders with military authority.
He wanted the female chengguan members, China's burly urban policemen, feared and despised for their capricious crackdowns and penchants for violence, to communicate a certain impression to a handful of onlookers.
"Firm!"
"Attention!"
Show them, she whispered, "what pretty girls are like!"
Four girls who barely made their teens in white gloves and identical olive green jackets and tight pants to attract attention.
Four pairs of black shoes perfectly aligned.
Four elegant hats placed perfectly above the hair tied with blue and white striped bows.
"Personally, I think they have a normal appearance," Mr. Tang said, disdainfully.
"The models are cute."
More than one government has tried to clean up the image of China's urban inspectors.
One city mandated that all new recruits have a bachelor's degree.
Guangdong Province changed the grayish-green color of the uniforms to a supposedly more attractive blue.
Wuhan, in central China, replaced the use of force with intimidating looks: In 2009, according to one report, 50 officers surrounded a wayward snack cart, and watched it with a constant frown for half an hour, until the street vendor gathered his things and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 people in Chengdu, has chosen a radical makeover.
Since 2003, the district has added 13 women to its urban police, expressly chosen for their appearance, proportion and youth.
The idea is to give the rough police a softer, feminine side.
Unfortunately, even Scarlett Johansson would have to fight to increase China's slightest respect for these city squads.
And for good reason, critics would argue.
Unlike the police, these officers are authorized only to enforce city ordinances, imposing fines and other administrative penalties.
But Chinese news outlets routinely portray a different reality.
In January 2008, inspectors in Hubei Province beat a passerby to death after he used his cellphone to film them breaking up a protest against a landfill.
Last year, a training manual for inspectors in Beijing was stolen and posted online, describing how to effectively whip criminals without making them bleed.
This year, a Shanghai watermelon peddler suffered brain damage after a scuffle with five officers.
A violence-filled video game, available for download online, features Chinese-trained inspectors attacking street vendors.
"Chengguan has left a scar on the government," China Daily, a national publication, lamented last year after another controversy over tactics.
The newspaper demanded "a really meticulous cleaning."
Skeptics say the current approach is a long way from this.
After the district solicited through a notice eight new female recruits in October, an editorial in The Beijing Evening News questioned whether women had royal duties or were simply a stage distraction.
The answer seems to be a bit of both.
The district ad asked for female candidates ages 18 to 22, with a good figure "and all five harmonious facial features."
They had to be above average tall, greater than 1.6 meters or 5 feet, 2 1/2 inches.
Retirement at the age of 26 is mandatory.
Officials said the work was physically too arduous for women over 25.
"Your image is the important thing," an anonymous district official told Rednet.com, a quasi-government website.
"First, the external qualities of the candidates will determine whether they meet the requirements, such as height, weight, facial features, etc."
Then comes temperament "and inner qualities."
Female chengguan are like vases, he said, adding, "in addition to being vases, they will have other responsibilities."
Zheng Lihua, deputy director of the district city administration office, is not eager to endorse that description.
But he noted that height demands were standard in many Chinese job advertisements for both sexes.
Then comes the demand for harmonious facial features.
Whether this means being handsome is a matter of debate among the Chinese.
Surely, the disabled or disfigured should not appear.
"We can't allow a lame person or a hunchback to come to work here," Mr. Zheng said.
"His image wouldn't be right."
