Can civility bridge divisions?
After a remarkable campaign of invective and negativity, some civility has been unleashed this week in Washington.
Is it a harbinger of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to partisan combat in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no breakthrough on the big issues that need to be addressed during the outgoing session.
But from what everyone is saying, it was at least a polite discussion about the two sides' differences, as well as an acknowledgment of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than being another empty episode to score partisan points.
Wednesday's public meeting of the president's deficit committee was similarly civilized, despite remaining political differences among members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months generated a mutual respect that transcends the ideological divide that still separates members.
That is barely enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Now both sides are on a trial period, probing each other for signs of cooperativism and compromise, as they try to gauge the limits of public opinion and voters' patience for renewed partisan warfare.
Reason why Tuesday's meeting and the subsequent evaluations of it by the participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and deeply entrenched to suggest any rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it's taxes, spending, health care or welfare, the two sides are at opposite poles.
Still, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
"There's no question that things have changed with respect to the way we say things," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
"They are inevitable after the elections.
Elections arouse partisan passions, which are then extinguished.
That's good."
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the outgoing session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of this.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all of the reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to expand unemployment benefits, probably because Republicans cannot make believe they favor tax cuts for the wealthy, denying unemployment benefits for unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, there is heightened optimism about a possible deal on these issues during the outgoing session, along with ratification of the new nuclear disarmament pact START (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty).
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution cautions that successful cooperation on the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continued bipartisanship when the new 112th. Congress meets in January.
On the contrary, he stated that it is very likely and even inevitable that a period of disagreement will begin.
"After the things that need to be done are carried out, in the short term psychology will revert the situation to one of confrontation," he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) that civility can lead to true cooperation.
"I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as a rehearsal for the main event of 2012," he said.
The reasons have a lot to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters of the Tea Party, who contributed decisively to its creation.
As aware as Republican leaders are of the dangers of exaggerating their position, they know they must try to fulfill their promises to cut state spending and strike down the new health care law.
Those party lines are already clearly seen in the initial reactions to the deficit commission's recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and raising some taxes and the retirement age, and cutting spending.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, by their own assessment, have forcibly put the issue of the deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member commission to release their plan as an official recommendation, and have been struggling to get close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among the officials elected on the panel, suggesting that on fiscal issues there is, at least currently, little basis or desire for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between White House Republicans and those in Congress.
The first will happen next year in the form of partisan clashes, when Republicans challenge Obama on the budget, taxes and health care, followed by a period of increased bipartisan cooperation.
What would cause change?
Public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If confrontation leads to a stalemate, as happened in 1995, then both parties will watch the reaction of the people closely.
Whoever they think is losing will likely change course and seek compromise.
However, this may be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and congressional Republicans than there was between President Bill Clinton and Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as merely a prelude to a more momentous election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilism on display this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on the part of both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
