Without detracting from the skill as a driver of the eventual champion, the German Sebastian Vettel, nor from the capacity of the Renault engine that propels his car, in the world of Formula 1 has become a legend the "secret weapon" that the multinational Siemens has put in the hands of Red Bull to turn it into a winning team.
It is actually a powerful process simulation software that the German company put on the market in 2007 for purposes far removed from high automotive competition.
Called PLM, this powerful computer tool has been used to design assembly lines for manufacturing factories around the world, power plants, high-precision instruments.
The objective is to reproduce, faithfully simulate the product or process before building it in a real way, thus avoiding failures and avoidable expenses.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi aircraft or Nissan's most celebrated utility cars.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens' industrial division, explains that the use of this computer tool in its Formula 1 factory has allowed Red Bull to design and carry out "in a few hours, almost in real time", the modifications, changes and improvements that are detected during races and in tests.
Russwurm explains that the teams in 1992 had an average of 10 technicians in their team who were able to make a maximum of three or four improvements to the vehicles during each season.
The Red Bull team currently employs 180 highly qualified young professionals who, equipped with powerful computer equipment, analyze and project all kinds of modifications to the cars.
The Siemens executive explained that PLM software is capable of analyzing and improving all elements of Red Bull cars with the exception of the engine, which is the sole responsibility of Renault.
Materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety elements are modified.
Changes can be brought from simulator virtual reality to reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced laser production systems and high-tech autoclaves.
The only limitation to this madness of technological improvement is the figure of 40 million dollars that each Formula 1 team can spend at most in each season to facilitate competition.
Red Bull has set up the high-tech factory to design and produce its cars in a town about 50 kilometers from London.
These are two buildings in which visits are restricted, especially for journalists.
Everything that happens there is considered "top secret".
The workforce for this task amounts to 580 people, including its two drivers, champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
Red Bull's Formula 1 hero is undoubtedly recent champion Sebastian Vetell.
Among the immense technological resources that the energy drink brand has put at the service of its participation in the circuits, there are other protagonists whose contest is invaluable and their notoriety null.
The factory's chief technology officer, Steve Nevey, says that five years ago it could be said that R+D advances in wagon cars accounted for 50% of the victories and the drivers were responsible for the rest.
Today these percentages have varied and technology accounts for 85% of success, while pilots contribute 15% of the added value.
Nevey acknowledges that the Vettel or Webber will never be replaced by computer science since "they are unpredictable gladiators."
