On the other hand, Vice President Elena Salgado, with the support of former President Felipe González, has joined the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel for her responsibility in unleashing the current crisis.
How should these movements be interpreted?
It goes without saying that Merkel's position is not a mistake in her communication policy.
On the contrary, it is another twist in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And there Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which clashes with that of maintaining the old traditions of many of its partners.
In the face of European resistance, in Germany there is beginning to be speculation about the three possible solutions to the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, composed of itself, Austria and the Netherlands, among other countries, while the south would leave the currency zone.
The second, the recovery of the framework, although it now seems science fiction, with a very favorable current of opinion, close to 50% of the population.
The third, a redesign of the euro, in line with German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, budgetary rigour, fines for offending countries, possible suspensions of payments by some of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been defined for some time, so there are no excuses now.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were stimulating deficits, the German government pulled out of its sleeve a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany believed should be done (plans for fiscal rigour and stability in public finances), and what its European partners, including France, were practicing.
The second on the forehead was given by the Central European country when Merkel painfully prolonged the decision to rescue Greece.
Even then it was the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public and published opinion were very much against the bailout of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel again emerges with a clear position, demanding the reform of the Union's treaties, to make it possible to rescue a country and, at the same time, force private lenders to bear part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it has precipitated the Irish crisis and everything else.
But your proposal, although somewhat sweetened, has been approved and, in the coming months, we should witness the process of reforming the Union that makes those measures possible from 2013 onwards.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And he is telling us all that, although measures have to be taken now, with which he may not agree very much, from that date the old operation of the euro will be over.
2013 will mean the birth of a new currency area, in which offending countries will be severely punished, may be forced to declare themselves in default and, in that case, the private sector will also bear part of the cost.
Germany is signaling to us that we must follow a severe growth path with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness, and positive external balances.
Another alternative based on debt and construction, with huge holes in the balance of payments, like the one that has presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, will simply not tolerate it.
The challenge is clear.
And we would be wrong not to understand it.
It is not just a question of bringing the public deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What they demand of us is much harder.
And the worst thing we could do in these circumstances is deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will give way to greater calm.
And that we take advantage of the window of opportunity they have given us, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also understood this and his double manifesto (the reforms promised after last Saturday's meeting with large companies and yesterday's announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite the criticism of Merkel, the thesis that we must put order at home has made its way.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and it does not seem that they will move it.
And, among the possibilities contemplated, that of leaving a currency zone too crowded with unserious countries, cannot be excluded.
Then, Germany will always be able to tell us that it had already warned us.
Sport and fraud of law
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax show ingenuity but no willingness to escape a penalty.
The expulsion allegedly engineered by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League has led to rivers of ink being written about whether or not such behaviour is unsportsmanlike and whether, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, with a few minutes left in the game (which his team had already clearly won), the two players deliberately lost time when drawing fouls to cause the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid will finish as leader of its group, both players will serve the regulatory sanction the next match of the league, against Auxerre, and will be able to pass clean cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee has sanctioned the team's coach, José Mourinho, with two matches and the players involved with different economic amounts.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather frequent in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the unwritten rules, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate that arose in the case is due to the fact that it has been carried out by a team of the Real Madrid entity (which in its anthem boasts nobility and honor, and that on past occasions has fined its players for similar acts) and to the dramatization orchestrated, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to his long history as a histrionic and provocative coach.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of behavior not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions commit fraud of law; Well, in effect, they are actions that respect the sporting regulations, but they seem to evade their meaning.
The question is to examine the kind of damage they cause to sportsmanship.
One of the goods that comprises the sportsmanship is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions was not endangered, that is, there was no violent play.
Another of these goods that is alluded to with fair play is to prevent the team of the offending players from taking unfair advantage of the opposing team, which also did not happen.
Now, the paradox of the action of the Real Madrid players is that he did not accommodate what we normally characterize as cheating or fraud of law, because his violation of the rules was not done secretly to try to avoid the sanction, but precisely his action tried to be the most obvious in order to receive the punishment of the referee.
They hoped and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders obtain in the intentional faults examined.
Here it seems necessary to verify that the rival is not placed at a disadvantage or benefit is obtained in the same game, because obviously the result of the action means leaving the team itself with fewer players.
And it is not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club will not be able to count on those players.
The advantage, obviously, is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But it is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, because the team can be eliminated at the first change, and also with this performance the players serve a sanction match and go to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension for accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, if you go through rounds, it is not so clear that it is an advantage.
In short, these actions do not go against sportsmanship, which does include making strategic decisions that favor making the most of what the rules allow.
In the case at hand, the players did not act to evade the application of the sanction (this would be a clear case of fraud of law), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding punishment or fleeing it.
Although the boundary between ingenuity and fraud of law is blurred, on this occasion I think it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises from two factors: because it was two self-expulsions and because of the way in which the directive to provoke them was transmitted.
The damage done to the principles of sport by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
Offensive of offers to capture the Christmas dinners of groups in BCN
The dictatorship of the calendar concentrates this year an avalanche of reserves for the 16th and 17th.
Self-paid celebrations proliferate by employees, who want to spend between 20 and 30 euros.
Like nougat and lottery, with the arrival of December also return the group dinners prior to Christmas, which continue to act as an oxygen balloon for the restoration and leisure of Barcelona, but because of the crisis have led to an offensive of adjusted prices to be able to capture the majority customer:  Almost everyone wants to spend between 20 and 30 euros on dinners or lunches, agree the entrepreneurs and associations of the sector interviewed.
To finish complicating the accounting, this year's calendar (when New Year's Eve falls on Friday) has concentrated the requests in the week of December 13, with the result to date of an avalanche of dinner reservations for peak days (the 16th and 17th) and hardly movement for the previous week.
As has been happening since 2008, when the lean season began, there are many companies that have eliminated collective dinners for budgetary reasons.
In order not to dispense with tradition, many workers keep it paying out of their own pocket.
Whatever the situation, both demand battle prices, confirms the president of the Gremi de Restauració de Barcelona, Gaietà Farràs.
The representative of the employers, today, does not dare to predict how the celebrations will be this month.
"People think long before booking."
"He wants to get out but he has the alerts on the issue of prices," he says.
The business will go well "to those who give quality at a good price and with good service," he adds, and recalls that customers tend to go down a step with the crisis, so that the range around 25 euros has become the majority in demand.
In a survey in various downtown establishments, the collapse of petitions for the night of the 17th is verified.
In the Soteras group indicate that there is a real boom of requests for that Friday, with the intention of spending less than 30 euros, to which they have responded by adapting their menus to the situation, with complete formulas of 25 to 35 euros.
