They also see green shoots in some companies that reinvite their employees and a feeling that the volume of the groups is somewhat higher.
On the part of the Fecasarm employer (which includes entities such as the Association of Bars, Restaurants and Leisure of Barcelona), its vice president, Enric Gomà, hopes to begin to see the end of the tunnel and maintains that as a whole the reservations are "encouraged", although customers "negotiate to the maximum".
Of course, the illusion for the celebrations has not decreased, whoever pays, he says.
Pakistan's nuclear program raises major concern in U.S.
Islamabad produces atomic weapons at "a faster rate than any other country."
The Wikileaks leaks confirm links between the Taliban and Pakistan.
The content of the correspondence between the US embassy in Pakistan and the US State Department leaked by the Wikileaks portal confirms the enormous concerns caused in Washington by the Pakistani nuclear program.
Apart from the illuminating and juicy details they offer about the content of the conversations and the thoughts of the American diplomatic representatives accredited in Islamabad, the documents reveal that cooperation between the two countries in the field of atomic security, instead of increasing, "decreases", and that the unstable Asian country produces nuclear weapons "at a faster rate than any other country in the world".
The particularity of Pakistan's nuclear program - that weapons are not assembled but remain stored in components to make them difficult to destroy in case of attack - is one of the main reasons for vigilance in Washington.
This is how the ambassador to Pakistan, Anne W. Patterson, lists it in a report prior to the visit of the then National Security Advisor, James Jones: "The proximity of some nuclear facilities to territory under Taliban attack, the rumored dispersion of nuclear materials and the vulnerability of the transport of atomic materials."
The high number of people involved in nuclear arsenals and missile programs is regarded, not only by the United States, but also by Russia, as proliferating and a reason to maintain vigilance.
"Pakistan has had to hire personnel with strict religious beliefs to protect nuclear facilities; given the drop in educational and cultural levels, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recruit people to work in nuclear or missile programs," Russian Foreign Ministry expert Yuri Korolev said at a meeting with his U.S. counterparts.
The most novel of the documentation leaked by Julian Assange's website is the decreasing cooperation between the US and Pakistan on issues of nuclear proliferation and the high pace of Pakistani production of nuclear weapons.
An embassy dispatch in May, which describes communication with Pakistan as "frustrating", states: "Transparency is often non-existent; Offers of help go unanswered or are discarded."
In another message, Peter Lavoy, National Intelligence official for South Asia, notes that "despite the economic catastrophe, Pakistan produces nuclear weapons at a faster rate than any other country in the world."
Ambassador Patterson also asks Washington, during a visit by the head of the Army, General Ashfaq Kayani, to make it "very clear" to the person in charge that "the Pakistan Army must end tacit support for terrorist groups."
Hunting for the head of Wikileaks
Obama appoints a senior counterterrorism official to prevent further leaks.
Interpol issues a red alert in order to follow the movements and locate Assange wherever he is.
Everything related to Wikileaks and its founder, Julian Assange, forms a complicated labyrinth where it is difficult to have certainty about the facts.
Yesterday Interpol issued a "red alert" to "locate and follow the movements" of Assange.
However, this is not a traditional arrest warrant.
In addition, it is not new, but dates from November 20.
And it has nothing to do with the latest leak of more than a quarter of a million US diplomatic documents but with the accusations of sexual abuse that the Australian faces in Sweden.
In addition, the lawyer of the creator of Wikileaks, Mark Stephens, assures that "the police know where and how to contact Mr. Assange".
It was on the 20th when the international police force based in Lyon (France) issued the order at the request of Sweden, but did not reveal it until yesterday, after receiving authorization from the authorities of that country.
Thus, the 188 countries of Interpol have indications to identify or locate Assange "with a view to his provisional arrest and extradition".
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of an individual affected by a red alert, many of the member countries, as explained by the organization, do consider the so-called red notice free way to proceed with an arrest – which must be undertaken by the national police force – especially if they have a bilateral extradition agreement, as is the case of Sweden and England.  where Assange is believed to be.
The movement has outraged Assange's lawyers, who yesterday published a letter denouncing that the 39-year-old Wikileaks founder has shown himself willing to respond by videoconference to questions from Swedish authorities.
They also remember that Assange requested and obtained permission to leave Sweden from the prosecutor in his case, whom they compare with the mythical Lavrentiy Pavlovich Beria, Stalin's security chief.
"This looks like a hunt, not a legal persecution," the letter said.
While the world searches for him – and from Australia his mother defends the innocence of her son – Assange remains missing, but not silent.
On Monday he gave an interview to the editor of Time magazine via Skype, a conversation in which he called for the resignation of US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton.
"If it can be shown that he was responsible for ordering American diplomats to spy on the UN in violation of international treaties that the US has signed, he should resign," he said.
His opinion was reviled yesterday by White House press secretary Robert Gibbs, who called the resignation call "ridiculous and absurd."
"I'm not entirely sure why we should care about the opinion of a guy with a website," he told CNN.
Obama himself has commissioned a senior official in the fight against terrorism, Russell Travers, to prevent further leaks of documents.
President Barack Obama's spokesman's attempt to downplay Assange contrasts with views now proclaimed by conservative politicians and commentators.
Peter King, the congressman who from January will chair the House Homeland Security Committee, has asked the State Department to study the possibility of including Wikileaks on the list of terrorist organizations "to intervene and their funds and pursue anyone who gives them any contribution or aid."
Still further has gone Tom Flanagan, an adviser to Canadian President Stephen Harper, who has had to back down after saying Assange should "be killed."
"Obama should target it and use a drone or something."
The one who did not apologize was Mike Huckabee, Baptist minister, former governor of Arkansas and possible candidate for president.
"Whoever in the government leaked the information is guilty of treason and anything other than execution would be too kind punishment," he said on Fox.
Puigcercós seeks peace in ERC with winks to those related to Carod
The Republican leader will allow the party a secret ballot on its continuation.
Huguet proposes a more plural executive and the end of the assembly system.
Joan Puigcercós seems to have found the recipe to overcome the umpteenth internal revolt in the ranks of ERC, without north for the loss of 11 deputies and half of the votes.
The president of the party is aware that his threat of resignation is insufficient for those related to former leader Josep Lluís Carod-Rovira, but he also knows that the influence of that sector is today as diluted as his own mentor and that it can not cause him the headaches he had with other extinct currents.
Therefore, the leader of Esquerra will try to win over the new critics with winks that allow him to shield himself until the municipal elections.
To begin with, Puigcercós announced yesterday that the more than 200 national councilors of ERC will be able to pronounce on their continuity in secret.
By means of ballots, and not by show of hands.
If the carodists want to convey a certain vote of punishment to the president, they can do so without fear of reprisals.
In fact, the leader of the ranks wants to avoid the image of division as much as that of submission to his person.
In several interviews, he said that it would not be considered ratified with half plus one of the votes, but added, without specifying percentages, that a result "a la Bulgarian" would not be good either.
Those close to Carod demand from the president something more than putting his position at the disposal of the militancy, a gesture that is not valid when Puigcercós controls the highest body between congresses.
But not having enough majority to force resignations, they will try to agree with the executive on a road map by May.
To this end, they hope to participate in the preparation of the strategic reorientation document that the leadership will submit to the vote of the national council on the 18th.
His intention is to endorse Puigcercós in exchange for him promising to advance the congress to autumn 2011, something that the dome already takes for granted.
The ERC leader acknowledged that "polyphony" harms stability and that his goal is to make the organization capable of washing dirty laundry from doors inwards once and for all.
In this line, the article that the acting Minister Josep Huguet signed on his blog is symptomatic.
Considered the ideologue of Puigcercós, the head of Innovació took it for granted that the leader will be endorsed "in exchange for various objectives."
And he listed five, of which two stand out.
The first, to "recompose" the executive so that it represents at least 90% of the militancy, that is, to include new faces that come from the sector related to Carod.
The second may be the great novelty.
Huguet proposes that ERC liquidate once and for all the assembly as a mechanism of operation.
Thus, it advocates a reform of the statutes that allows congresses to be held through delegates elected by suffrage.
Ending the assembly model, an exception in the Spanish party system, has been an obsession of Puigcercós' team, which already fought in this sense in the last two congresses.
In fact, the convulsive conclave of 2008 left the task to the leadership to review the assembly in a specific congress of reform of statutes.
This appointment is still pending, because the internal tide of recent years advised against facing the matter.
Now, with no critical sectors lurking, it may be a good time to pick it up again and try to shut it down for good.
