In addition, it is necessary to label resources to detonating tourism projects that contribute to giving security to the state and in the update to the Alcohol Law that they have not been able to solve in previous legislatures.
A wizard king is wanted
Dolls, cars and bicycles, among other toys, are the desire of the children of the Coronado Valenzuela family.
For his parents, next Three Kings Day it will be difficult to please their illusions, since their home is made up of nothing more and nothing less than 12 people and a goat.
However, Adelaide, Isabel, Jesus, José Alfredo, María Guadalupe, Isaías, José Juan and Miguel do not lose hope that Melchor, Gaspar and Baltazar will give them the toys and clothes they so desire.
The family lives in a humble house in Colonia Salvador Allende and lives day to day because the father does not have a permanent job.
"Well, sometimes we look tough because my husband doesn't have a jacket, but we sell tangerine and potato... already in the afternoon I go out with the 'plebes' to sell on the street," said Cayetana Valenzuela Andrade, mother of the children.
Adelaide, 4, wants a doll or a bike, while her sister Isabel, 3, would like a Barbie doll.
For his part, José Alfredo, 10, has long aspired to have a 'monster' car and for his little brother Jesus, 8 months old, Cayetana suggests clothes size for a year.
"He (José Alfredo) told me, 'I would like this monster,' but I told him 'let's see son,' because it was very expensive," Cayetana recalled sadly.
For older children, who were in school, clothing and footwear would be ideal.
Maria Guadalupe, 11, is size 12; Isaiah, 10, is size 10, while Miguel, 8, wears size eight.
José Juan, 14, lacks tennis, so a pair of size five and a half or six would be very helpful.
If you want to help make the dream of the children of the Coronado Valenzuela family come true, you can participate in the campaign A Wizard Wanted by donating a toy or cash at the Northwest reception.
Fourteen suspected drug traffickers arrested
On Wednesday, in Estrie, a dozen persecutions have been carried out in the framework of the dismantling of a network of production and sale of Cannabis.
Fourteen people have been arrested and will face various charges.
The persecutions have occurred in Sherbrooke, Orford and Stoke, mainly in the places where the drug was produced.
"Around 750 cannabis plants, four kilos of hashish, money and equipment intended for production have been seized," says Louis-Philippe Ruel, spokesman for Quebec Security.
In total, eleven men and three women have been arrested, including the two alleged leaders of the network, two men from Sherbrooke.
The detainees had to appear at the Sherbrooke courthouse within hours of their arrest.
They could face charges of cannabis production, possession for the purpose of trafficking, conspiracy and theft of services, among others.
These persecutions have occurred after a long investigation that has lasted about a year.
"It was the information provided by the public that allowed us to make the arrests," says Mr. Ruel.
Around seventy officers from the Estrie Research Module of Quebec Security, the Sherbrooke Police Service and the Memphrémagog Police Department participated in this police operation.
Illegal migration can be fought without problems
The Conservatives' bill, which the government says should solve the problem of boats loaded with clandestine migrants, is sure to face strong opposition, as all three opposition parties announced on Wednesday that they could not support it.
"I rely primarily on the Charter."
"I find myself here with a party that has created the granite you tread," said Liberal leader Michael Ignatieff, surrounded by MPs after the weekly caucus meeting.
The Liberals argue that the bill in its current form, which would allow anyone who comes from a ship identified as transporting clandestine immigrants for up to a year, violates the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms.
Quebec Bloc leader Gilles Duceppe also said he could not back the bill because it targets the wrong target.
"We are against it and, apparently, all the opposition parties are against the project, so we will see what the government does," said Mr. Duceppe.
NPD immigration critic Olivia Chow has dismissed with the stroke of a pen criticism that her party is not firm enough on illegal immigrants.
"The New Democrats agree that action should be taken against those in charge of clandestine boats and that is what we intend with another bill, the C-35," says Ms. Chow.
"We don't support the Conservatives' bill because it targets refugees and imprisons children for a minimum of one year," explains Ms Chow.
Immigration Minister Jason Kenney has accused the parties of playing politicians and ignoring the will of Canadians.
"The vast majority of Canadians tell MPs that they do not tolerate this kind of clandestine migration, these criminal operations against Canada and that they treat the country like a doormat."
"They expect Canada to take strong action," says Minister Kenney.
The government has not announced a confidence vote on its bill, which could lead the country to an election as a result of its rejection.
However, a conservative has told the QMI Agency that the Government was going to request a vote so that each MP who will oppose it is then explained to their constituents.
The new unity does not achieve unanimity
Despite the announcement of the possible creation of a permanent unit to combat corruption and collusion by Jean Charest, many observers continue to call for the establishment of a public consultation commission on the issue.
The Minister of Public Security, Robert Dutil, supports that this idea has not been raised two days ago: Quebec would have consulted with the Department of Investigation of New York this issue since January of last year.
The metropolis has had a permanent anti-corruption unit since 1870.
Consequently, Tuesday's announcement has caught more than one by surprise.
It should be noted that, during a meeting of the Permanent Council on the Quebec Police Services held on October 29, this measure was never discussed despite the presence of Robert Dutil.
That was enough for Stéphane Bergeron, critic of the Quebec party that deals with the issue of public security, to describe this announcement as "a rabbit out of the hat" and as "a botched last-minute solution."
Minister Dutil, for his part, has responded to those who fear that political power will have too much influence over possible future unity.
"You'll see the results when we announce it," he says simply.
"We are aware of this problem."
For the president of the CSQ, Réjean Parent, there is nothing that can replace the launch of a public survey.
"The more Mr. Charest persists in preventing the creation of this commission of inquiry, the more people share our opinion, that is, that he has something to hide," he explains.
"The only way to have a commission of inquiry is with the resignation of Jean Charest," explains Yves Boisvert, professor of ethics and governance at the National School of Public Administration.
To break this impasse, he suggested that Quebec should give a special mandate to the comptroller general to conduct a survey on collusion and corruption.
"We must be able to extend the mandate of the Comptroller General," he concludes.
It also considers that Quebec could give the financial controller the same powers as a commissioner, thus allowing him to compel persons to testify.
The creation of a permanent crew is not the only project in the making in the Charest government.
Quebec also requests Ottawa to amend the Criminal Code to make it more adapted to this type of crime.
This request appears to come from the prosecutor of Operation Marteau, who has informed Minister of Justice Jean-Marc Fournier that jurisprudence is not explicit in such investigations.
The Federal Minister for Public Security, Vic Toews, has confirmed that his counterpart in Justice, Rob Nicholson, is currently inclined to make certain amendments in relation to this issue.
During the Spring 2001 operation related to biker groups, although the Penal Code had not been adapted, 131 people were arrested.
Ottawa subsequently pushed for the adoption of the Gangster Act.
Rivers under extreme surveillance
Several waterways are being closely monitored due to heavy rainfall that has been recorded in several regions of the province since Tuesday.
On Wednesday afternoon there was a landslide in Shawinigan, Mauricie.
As a preventive measure, two houses have been evacuated.
In the evening, there was another landslide in Saint-Lin-Laurentides, in Lanaudière.
A road collapsed.
From Tuesday to Wednesday night, several regions recorded heavy rainfall, between 40 and 70 millimeters of rain.
An additional 20 to 40 millimeters are expected between now and Thursday night, depending on the region.
The sectors north of the river and in the Outaouais valley were the most affected.
They could receive up to a total of 100 millimeters of rain.
Since this precipitation is added to the melting of the snow that had already accumulated in certain sectors, it is feared that several rivers will overflow.
On Wednesday night, Quebec's Civil Security unit issued alerts for the Ouareau and Achigan rivers in Lanaudière.
The northern rivers in Saint-Jérôme in the Laurentides and Chêne in Lotbinière have caused flooding in the past and are under surveillance.
In the Lanaudière region, heavy rainfall has caused some lakes to overflow in Sainte-Julienne, Sainte-Marcelline-de-Kildare and Rawdon.
In Saint-Calixte, heavy rains have washed away a temporary bridge.
As a preventive measure, ten residences have been evacuated.
In Outaouais, the overflow of certain lakes has led to the closure of several roads, particularly in the municipality of Mansfield-et-Pontefract.
The Civil Security unit remains on alert and monitors the situation closely, said Annik Bouchard, the security adviser.
The Quebec Flood Forecast Centre, meanwhile, issued announcements Wednesday announcing the strong flooding of several rivers, notably the Maskinongé, the Assomption, the Ouareau, the Achigan, the Batiscan and the Loup.
Dupont partially blamed
Quebec radio host Stéphane Dupont has suffered a setback before the Canadian Broadcasting Standards Council (CCNR) for controversial statements regarding welfare and Haitians, as well as for his foul language on the radio.
The CCNR considers that Mr. Dupont and his CHOI 98.1 FM team had the right to express their opinion, but certain statements contained "inaccurate social assistance information, unduly negative representation of Haitians, and foul language that should not be used in daytime broadcasts."
The Council also indicated that discussions on suicide, including the disclosure of the names of two persons who had committed suicide, do not infringe broadcasting codes.
The CCNR had received several complaints regarding comments made on broadcasts broadcast between 2008 and 2010.
The first decision was issued following a complaint by the Common Front of people receiving social assistance from Quebec.
The group complained that the amounts mentioned in the issue were not correct.
Presenters must communicate reliable and not misleading data.
In relation to suicide, the presenter Stéphane Dupont had stated that suicide was an act of cowardice.
Most members of the Committee had concluded that the message conveyed was that suicide should not be seen as a solution to life's problems.
"The majority of the Committee considers that the episodes called into question in 'Dupont le midi' have treated a sensitive subject in an equitable and appropriate manner."
Consequently, any blame has been dismissed in this regard.
The last dispute concerned statements made following the earthquake in Haiti.
At that time, Stéphane Dupont and Jean-René Dufort had staged a media confrontation that had provoked numerous reactions.
The CHOI anchor stated that he had not made any donations to help Haitians because he could not know for sure if those in need would actually receive the money.
The Committee considers that these comments are not abusive, but that their cumulative effect constitutes an unduly negative representation of Haitians.
"I've already served my three-day suspension up there."
"My file has been clean for a year and a half," the presenter said.
In all decisions, the Committee denounces the issuance of foul language.
In any case, the CHOI-FM radio station has collaborated "even more than required".
The consequences will be minimal for the broadcaster, which must, among other things, announce the decisions once in prime time within three days.
A king of kung-fu in Montreal
The Montrealer of Algerian origin Nacereddine Zemmal has had an extremely peculiar route.
The athlete, who excels in "sanda" (kung-fu "full contact"), kickboxing and Thai boxing, climbs the tatami and rings of the world in search of new challenges.
"I started practicing martial arts like kung-fu and kickboxing 12 years ago, in Algeria," said Zemmal, who has lived in the metropolis since 2008 to advance to the professional level.
"In my case, I look for combat everywhere because, for those who don't enjoy the ground game involved in mixed martial arts, there are few competitions in North America."
The athlete, who works as a security agent and as an employee of the UPS company, has recently given bad news to his rivals, winning two gold medals at the World Karate and Kickboxing Association (WKA) World Amateur Championships, held from October 23 to 30 in Edinburgh, Scotland.
"I won in the full contact kickboxing and Thai box categories," he explained.
"I am currently preparing to participate in the San Shou World Cup in China."
"They will invite athletes who have finished in the top four in the last world championship in each category."
"In 2009, I won the bronze medal in Toronto."
"In 2005, in Vietnam, I finished eighth."
"In 2007, in China, I finished the tournament in fifth place, but I reached third place in Toronto in 2009," he added.
"The interesting thing is that I've been progressing in every competition."
"At this rate, I will be the first one this time or next year!"
