Clotilde Reiss affair: The Elysée has exaggerated Syria's mediation
For more than ten months, between July 2009 and May 2010, the fate of Clotilde Reiss, the young French researcher detained in Iran for "espionage", has had the public in suspense in France, has alerted diplomacy and has accentuated the deterioration of relations between Paris and Tehran.
All under the watchful eye of U.S. diplomats.
US documents obtained by WikiLeaks and consulted by Le Monde reveal certain unknown aspects of this crisis.
They describe how the Elysée has explained his strategy to the Americans to the point of giving them advice on managing their own "hostage" crises in Iran (a small group of senderistas).
They show how French officials tried to convince Washington that the release of the young Frenchwoman did not occur in exchange for the release of Majid Kakavand, an Iranian detained in France and wanted by US justice for trafficking materials for the Iranian nuclear program.
Finally, they reveal the stark reality of how the French presidency tried to manipulate the media into the idea that Syrian President Bashar al-Assad had played a key role in the release of Clotilde Reiss.
Actually, he did nothing.
A diplomatic telegram drafted on 12 August 2009 in Paris is entitled "Iran: French commentary on how to handle hostage-taking cases".
The Elysée adviser for strategic affairs, François Richier, accompanied by the director of the Quai d'Orsay for North Africa and the Middle East, Patrice Paoli, spoke with the US diplomat Kathleen Allegrone.
They explain the French method.
They advise Americans to do the following to repatriate their own citizens forcibly held in Iran.
"Make noise", they say, "continually drop" in the media the words "fundamental human rights", "innocence", "immediate release".
All to embarrass the Iranian regime, careful of its image.
"When the Iranians ask you to stop, do it even more often."
Because, once the attempts at negotiation through discreet channels are exhausted, "silence will not solve anything," the Iranians are "experts in delaying maneuvers."
Mr Richier adds that the detention of foreigners is "a common Iranian tactic: hostage-taking for political blackmail."
It announces that the release from prison of Clotilde Reiss (which will take place on August 16, the day she will take refuge in the French embassy) "will require the payment to the Iranians of a large amount of money" (230,000 euros of reward).
In addition, he points out that the Elysée anticipates other hostage crises, a phenomenon that "will increase."
The Iranians could "in the near future arrest another of the nearly 1,800 French citizens living in Iran," he says.
August 28, 2009.
Clotilde Reiss leaves prison after twelve days, but is blocked in Iran.
The following information is disseminated: Iranian Majid Kakavand, whose extradition is requested by the United States for illicit trafficking of sensitive electronic material into Iran, has been released in Paris by decision of a judge.
The U.S. embassy, like many observers, doubt this strange coincidence.
For Washington, which surrounds Iran's clandestine networks acquiring material for the nuclear program, the release of Majid Khakavand is bad news.
Has France accepted an exchange?
Release the Iranian in exchange for the French?
During a new conversation with Kathleen Allegrone, on September 4, François Richier guarantees that this was not the case.
The Elysée, he says, has not only "been greatly surprised by the judge's decision," but has tried to oppose it.
"There have been intense negotiations between the French presidency and the Minister of Justice" (at the time, Michèle Alliot-Marie), but "the French government cannot annul the decision" of the courts, he says.
Mr Richier also wants to show that Majid Kakavand is still under the "close" surveillance of the French intelligence services.
The Elysée adviser dials a phone number, hangs up and then informs the US diplomat that the Iranian "is currently in buildings in Paris managed by the Iranian embassy."
During the arrest of Clotilde Reiss in Iran, the Elysée spares no effort, using communiqués and "escapes" organized in the media to make believe that Syrian President Bashar Al-Assad plays an "important" and "influential" role of "mediator".
The Americans observe this activity with a certain irony and see that the manipulation bears fruit, since several newspaper articles transmit the official French version.
A telegram dated August 25, 2009 mentions "the media blitz of French officials."
Why such "gratitude" to Mr. Assad, asks the embassy in Paris.
"Despite his praise-laden statements, French officials privately acknowledge that they have only a vague idea of what the Syrians have actually done."
Next, the document discusses the reasons that have led the Elysée to give rise to this fiction.
The great communication effort "aims to validate Sarkozy's policy of opening up to Syria," he says.
A policy initiated in 2008, which "in the opinion of many critical voices in France and abroad, had just been branded as premature and undeserved."
By "exaggerating the Syrian role," Paris is trying to "show Syria the praise it can garner if it plays a constructive role in the region."
The goal is also to "sow the seeds of discord between Syria and Iran."
The U.S. Embassy knows this from a good source.
On August 11, François Richier confides to him: "Of course, we don't know if the Syrians have done anything or not."
"But anyway, we've thanked him."
"At the very least, this should cause confusion among Iranians."
