Avenging hackers and diligent spies
The WikiLeaks affair has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that only looks like a scandal in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes on an international scale and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let's go step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that every dossier created by a secret service (regardless of the nation to which it belongs) consists exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual mores only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and Gaddafi's ominously ridiculing profile has long been giving cabaret artists ideas to create their sketches.
The rule that secret files should only consist of publicly known news is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you visit a bookshop dedicated to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rosicrucians) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who dedicate themselves to the occult not only trust what they already know, which reconfirms what they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
The same applies to secret files.
The informant is lazy, just as the head of the secret services (if he could not be, what do I know, editor of the Libération) is lazy (or has little eagerness), who only considers true what he can recognize.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi sent by the U.S. Embassy in Rome to the State Department was the same as that published in Newsweek the week before.
So why have the revelations in these dossiers caused such a stir?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultivated person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since the Second World War and since Heads of State can call each other on the phone or take the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, except for some limited exercises of representation,  They have been transformed into centers of espionage.
Any viewer who watches investigative films knows this perfectly, we just pretend that we do not know it because of hypocrisy.
In any case, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of US diplomacy.
Second, the idea that any hacker can consult the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world greatly affects the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the "executioners".
But let us enter into the true nature of what has happened.
Formerly, in Orwell's time, it could be conceived of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy has come true since, being able to control every movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is demonstrated, as it is now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the avenger of the citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that can no longer even keep its own secrets be endured?
It is true, as Georg Simmel said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge of the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is in reality an empty secret, without secrecy, since it comes from the public sphere; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means taking away all power.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but it has, and very much, done Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to put any confidential information on the Internet, since it would be like publishing it on a poster in the middle of the street.
But it is also clear that, with today's technologies, you cannot expect to have confidential conversations over the phone.
Nothing is easier than to find out if and when a Head of State has travelled by plane and contacted one of his counterparts.
How will they be able to maintain private and confidential relationships in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the moment, my forecast is the stuff of science fiction and, therefore, novel, but I imagine government agents who move discreetly in diligences with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned by heart or, at most, hiding some data written on the heels of their shoes.
That information is then kept in a single copy, in locked drawers: after all, the Watergate spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology currently advances like a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph has revolutionized communications, the Internet has recreated a wired (telephone) telegraph.
Videotapes (analog) had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, moving forward and backward, discovering all the secrets of editing, whereas now (digital) CDs only allow you to move forward or backward from chapter to chapter, that is, to enormous proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can go from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the journeys that entails, we need three and a half hours.
It is therefore not out of the ordinary for politics and communication techniques to take us back to horse-drawn carriages.
One last comment.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was being hatched in secret in embassies.
At present, it is embassies that ask for confidential information from the press.
Climate: France's botched funding pledges
One year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to examine whether the rapidly released (so-called fast start) pledges made by developed countries have been respected.
And the French botches have been revealed.
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union pledged €7.2 billion over three years and France €1.26 billion (i.e. €420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put on the table its best cards to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start financing is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press conference, a large complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
Operation transparency was appreciable and was appreciated for what it really counts: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to meet its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But, if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Accord, the money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without harming official development assistance.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
At present, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission has taken 2009 as a reference: international funding is maintained and 150 million are added in three years as fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks for the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, no reference is made to the expenditures of previous years or to the total level of official development assistance.
In particular, the total amount of France's aid to developing countries may remain stable (or even decrease) while it claims to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element, the distribution between grants and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses the method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider every euro borrowed to be equivalent to one euro donated.
Obviously, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to emission reductions that are based on more efficient technologies), it is fallacious to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to one euro that is donated... At most, only the cost of the loan to the lending country (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate) should be counted towards their commitments.
But France does not find such reasoning useful: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of grants (36.1 million euros); check the EU document to see for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses it in 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes one euro to meet its commitment, France contributes only ten cents and considers the effort comparable.
A nice trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France is abusing twice: on the one hand, in relation to actions over time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
Spending only 36.1 million euros, it manages to give the impression that it spends 420 million "new and additional", as promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has dealt with arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to donate when they can simply lend?) and in the negotiations, since developing countries are not stupid...
The chapter on early financing is a relatively short-term minutiae in relation to the climate negotiations as a whole.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this is not the case.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early financing.
Firstly, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, especially, France could move forward the discussions on gambling in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter currently under discussion): we will not get rid of the question of "additionality" or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on this issue as it is on others.
We therefore have the hope of the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancún next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast starts and its vision of "additionality" and lending utilization would help improve the level of international confidence needed to advance negotiations.
Warning about pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old boy ingests 81 different chemicals in a day, according to a study published Wednesday by the association Générations Futures (the old movement for the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "do not have a statistically significant value taking into account the limited number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem treated", acquired in supermarkets of Oise and Paris between July and September the foods that a child of about ten years usually consumes in four meals and a snack a day.
These model meals, which respect official recommendations (five parts of fresh fruits and vegetables, three parts of dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day), as well as sweets, were examined in laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other contaminants.
The balance of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemical substances, of which 42 classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances susceptible to act as endocrine disruptors (PE), according to studies by various institutions such as the International Agency for Research on Cancer.
"Although, in virtually all cases, the legal limits for each of the chemicals are not exceeded individually, our study clearly shows that consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic and/or PE contaminants is a concern," the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three considered safe carcinogens, as well as about twenty residues that can damage the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, intended as a snack for school, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to Kenyan green beans, included in the meal, where the study has detected traces of a potent insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, Russian steak, canned tuna, and even loaf of bread or chewing gum were seasoned with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, tests discovered the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon slice was the most "nutritious" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the analysis of the plastic dish used to heat the food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The ultimate risk these "pollutant cocktails" pose to the consumer "is likely underestimated," the study says.
The Europe Ecology-Les Verts Alliance (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "in the face of the seriousness of the situation" to apply a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb "the increase in diseases associated with civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.
